\pard\f0\fs28  ({\b a}) Subsp. {\b dichotoma}: Basal leaves not in dense rosettes, green, pubescent. Flowers crowded, or sometimes separated by their own length; inflorescence 1 or 2(3) times dichotomously branched; upper bracts not ciliate. Petal-limb bifid for c. 2/3 of its length. 2n = 24.{\i  Throughout the range of the species, except Greece and the Aegean region}.
\par 

\pard\f0\fs28  ({\b b}) Subsp. {\b racemosa} (Otth) Graebner in Ascherson & Graebner, {\i Syn. Mitteleur. Fl. }{\b 5}({\b 2}): 93 (1920) ({\i S. racemosa} Otth, {\i S. sibthorpiana} Reichenb.): Basal leaves in dense rosettes, more or less densely grey-pubescent. Flowers less densely crowded; inflorescence often more branched; upper bracts ciliate. Petal-limb bifid almost to base.{\i  S.E. Europe}.
\par 

\par 

\pard\f0\fs28    Subsp. {\b euxina} (Rupr.) Coode & Cullen, {\i Notes Roy. Bot. Gard. Edinb.}{\b  28}: 8 (1967) ({\i S. euxina} Rupr.), from maritime sands of the N. Aegean and Black Sea, is similar to subsp. ({\b b}) but has narrower leaves, up to 8 mm wide. It probably does not merit subspecific recognition. The European plants have white petals ({\i S. euxina} var. {\i bulgarica} Jordanov & Panov), whereas they are usually pink in Asiatic material.
